{{Infobox military installation | name = Bengħisa Tower | native_name = Torri ta' Bengħisa | partof = the [[De Redin towers]] | location = [[Birżebbuġa]], [[Malta]] | image = | caption = | type = [[Coastal defence and fortification|Coastal]] [[watchtower]] | coordinates = {{coord|35|48|42.6|N|14|32|23|E|type:landmark|display=inline}} | ownership = | controlledby = | built = 1659 | used = | builder = [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]] | materials = [[Limestone]] | height = | fate = Demolished, 1915 | battles = | events = }}
'''Bengħisa Tower''' ({{lang-mt|Torri ta' Bengħisa}}), originally known as '''''Torre di Benissa'''''<ref>{{cite book|title=Ġrajjet Malta - It-Tielet Ktieb|date=2006|publisher=Department of Education|location=[[Sliema]]|page=81|edition=4|language=Maltese}}</ref> and also referred to as the '''Red Tower''' ({{lang-mt|Torri l-Aħmar}}), was a small [[watchtower]] in Bengħisa, limits of [[Birżebbuġa]], [[Malta]]. It was built in 1659 as the seventh of the [[De Redin towers]], on or near the site of a medieval watch post.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zammit|first1=Vincent|title=Fortifications in the Middle Ages|journal=Civilization|date=1984|volume=1|page=33|publisher=PEG Ltd|location=[[Ħamrun]]}}</ref> An [[Entrenchment (fortification)|entrenchment]] was built around the tower in 1761, and it was armed with 10 guns. The tower was demolished by the British to clear the line of fire of the nearby [[Fort Benghisa]] in 1915.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Guillaumier|first1=Alfie|title=Bliet u Rħula Maltin|date=1987|publisher=Valletta Publishing & Promotion Co. Ltd.|location=[[Valletta]]|page=104|language=Maltese}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mifsud |first1=A. |title=La Milizia e le Torri antiche di Malta |journal=Archivum Melitense |date=1920 |volume=4 |issue=2 |page=80 |url=http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Archivum%20Melitense/AM.04(1920)/AM.%204(1920)2/02.pdf |language=Italian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326211511/http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Archivum%20Melitense/AM.04(1920)/AM.%204(1920)2/02.pdf |archivedate=26 March 2017}}</ref>
[[File:Malta - Birzebbuga - Freeport (Triq Benghajsa) 07 ies.jpg|thumb|left|Oil tanks at the Malta Freeport, with the site of the tower roughly at the centre of this picture]] The site of the tower and the entrenchment is now occupied by oil tanks forming part of the [[Malta Freeport]].
