'''Galway Bay FM''' is an [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] [[Radio in Ireland#Independent local radio|independent local radio station]] and operates under a licence from the [[Broadcasting Commission of Ireland]].<ref name="bci">{{cite web|url=http://www.bci.ie/licensed_operators/local_radio_galway.html |title=Galway Bay FM Contact details |publisher=Broadcasting Commission of Ireland |accessdate=5 March 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090310035637/http://www.bci.ie/licensed_operators/local_radio_galway.html |archivedate=10 March 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> Established in 1989,<ref name="emigrant">{{cite web|url=http://old.emigrant.ie/article.asp?iCategoryID=200&iArticleID=34173 |title=August 20, 1989 THE IRISH EMIGRANT Issue No.133 |publisher=Emigrant Online |date=200-08-20 |accessdate=5 March 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071124121104/http://old.emigrant.ie/article.asp?iCategoryID=200&iArticleID=34173 |archivedate=24 November 2007 }}</ref> the station broadcasts from studios in [[Galway]], serving the city and [[County Galway]].

==Programming==
The programming format is a mixture of music, news, sport, current affairs and local issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tca.ie/controls/getimage.ashx?image_id=1604 |publisher=Competition Authority |title=DETERMINATION OF MERGER NOTIFICATION M/06/067 – CONNACHT TRIBUNE/GALWAY BAY FM |accessdate=5 March 2009 |date=24 October 2006 |format=pdf |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429080248/http://www.tca.ie/controls/getimage.ashx?image_id=1604 |archivedate=29 April 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> Programmes are generally in [[English language|English]], although the station features some [[Irish language]] programmes. There is an opt-out service with alternative programming for Galway city on weekday evenings using the 95.8&nbsp;MHz frequency.

==History==
The station was originally launched as '''Radio West'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/sale-of-local-radio-station-nets-galway-county-board-a-800000-windfall-66126.html|title=Sale of local radio station nets Galway county board a €800,000 windfall|publisher=Irish Independent|date=28 December 2006|accessdate=5 March 2009}}</ref><!-- Don't confuse with RAdio West, a 1980's pirate station--> and was the first legal local radio station in Galway.<ref name="emigrant"/> Radio West changed its name to Galway Bay FM in 1993.

In 2006, the ''[[Connacht Tribune]]'' newspaper bought the station outright, having previously owned 27% of it.

